description: A White Synapta Sea Cucumber. I found several of them the last few nights off the dock. In the dark they becomes extremely elongated and appear transparent save an opaque tube running down the center (presumably the digestive tract) and undulate their bodies near the surface of the water. After bringing them into the light they contract and sink to the bottom (which I guess is why I never see them during the day). This one was about 4 inches when contracted. The tentacle structure separates it from the similar looking Silky Cucumber and color separates it from the Pink Synapta.

description: Although seemingly ordinary-looking, this Sand Dollar did recently corner me in a coffee shop, and expound on the connections between whale song and String Theory for 45 minutes.  So, I think my ID is accurate.  RIP.

The lovely Sunflower Star can have up to 24 arms. Sometimes it seems to glow from within. It comes in shades of orange and brown, with dabs of violet. I'm always sad to see a gull eating one, arm by arm. It was great to find dozens of these today, since many have died with the sea star wasting disease.

The Red Sea Cucumber is a gorgeous shade of sunset orange, and is quite fascinating to watch while it's feeding, as it places each tentacle one by one into its mouth to remove its food. Interesting that the sea cucumber is an echinoderm.

description: Here are five small Green Sea Urchins. I love these spiny little vegetarian urchins, although the red and purple species are more elegant.
The Striped Sea Star is normally more vividly colored than this one, sometimes orange and black, and sometimes rose and gray. I don't find them very often.

I love the name of these sand dollars-- Eccentric! The yellowish one is dead, the dozen or so purple ones fully alive, and they lie on their sides in the sand to feed. Most beaches don't have sand dollars around here, but this beach has thousands!
This Fat Blood Star apparently has the sea star wasting disease that's killing so many beautiful sea stars along the Pacific Coast in the past few months.

This Strongylocentrotus pupuratus  is the Purple Sea Urchin, although it looks mostly red. Its spines are short, however. It's a rare sight here. I see many more farther west, for example at Salt Creek.

I was happy to find this Blood Star so healthy, along with a couple of other healthy ones. Lately I've only found Blood Stars with the sea star wasting disease, which is decimating the beautiful sea stars all along the Pacific Coast.
This sea star with seven arms was on the beach at low tide at Emu Bay on Kangaroo Island. I gently carried it closer to the water, and then noticed my gentle handling had caused it to drop its arm!

description: For more information on the habitat, vegetation, and weather of the area where I made this observation, please see the journal entry for April 28, 2012 here on iNaturalist. This was an amazing thing for me to get to see. I had never once before seen a live sand dollar, only the dead ones that litter the beaches as sea shells to collect. What looks like mud covering them is actually a fine layer of spiny, tube-like feet that is used in feeding. I was extremely interested to learn that these are just burrowing sea urchins. They lived in the tide pools along the beach alongside hermit crabs, other smaller crabs, barnacles, and mussels. Each one was about 2.5 inches across.

There were hundreds of Purple Sea Urchins visible in tide pools and in the intertidal zone during the minus tide today at Salt Creek. Most are about 2" across with bright purple spines. In my opinion, there were far more than last year or the year before, and I wondered if it has anything to do with Wasted Sea Star Syndrome decimating the predatory sea stars.

Small green cushion starfish in a tidal rock pool.
Pile of Kina shells about the rocks.

Pin cushion, short armed starfish on the sandy bottom in about 1.5m of water at low tide (a couple of unlucky specimens found at a depth of only 500mm and selected for photography).  Quite abundant, spaced about 300mm apart on sea floor.  Mainly 5 armed and dark green in colour.
Six armed, green, short armed starfish.
Shell of dead (human predator I think) Kina.

A number of black backed gulls were using the fishing technique of paddling about in shallow water until they spot something beneath the water.  They then leap up and dive down to it.  Both juveniles and adults exhibited their skills and were catching common cushion starfish from the sandy bottom, and somehow swallow them down whole.  (I had previously wondered why the starfish seemed most common at a depth of 1.5m or more - it appears that the gulls can pick them off from shallower depths.).  Practically no wind, so water relatively  still and clear.

Banded light orangey pink and reddy brown arms looking a bit like an animated backbone or millipede.  Counted about 7 arms coming out from underneath a stone at low tide (behind the sea anemone in the overview shot).
Lots of baby cushion starfish near a dead fish.
Green/orange pentagon shaped starfish.
Eleven armed starfish on sandy bottom in about 1.5m of water off Scorching Bay beach, at low tide.  Arms looked relatively long and narrow.

description:
Just because there is no picture of this species here yet. 
I don't understant why there is so little information about this species on the web, whereas is is very common throughout all the tropical Indian Ocean, from African coast to Philippines (al teast, to my knowledge). 

You can tell them from the obvious 5 greyish zig-zag sutures, and strong black spines (sometimes with a blue-greenish tinge : don't confuse it with Echinothrix or Centrostephanus). 
Young individuals often have strikingly asymmetrical spines. Oral surface is more clear. 

This picture was taken by Philippe Bourjon in Reunion Island lagoons (plage Jacques Tessier). 

For more informations, see the article I edited on the French Wikipedia (English translation to come...).
